A cyst that is localized in the region of the orbit and exhibits an epithelial lining with a keratin-filled lumen. Hair follicles are one of the adnexal structures that are commonly found in walls of dermoid cysts.
A reduction in the amount of galactose residues of N-glycans.
A focal clonic seizure is a type of focal motor seizure characterized by sustained rhythmic jerking, that is regularly repetitive.
Loss of myelin from peripheral nerves in a pattern that differs between right and left.

This sign is created by a nonenhancing thrombus in the dural sinus surrounded by triangular enhancing dura as seen on cross-section. The sign, seen on contrast-enhanced CT scan images, suggests dural sinovenous thrombosis. It is best seen on wider window settings. It is a reliable sign of sinus thrombosis but is seen only in 25-30% of these cases.
Muscular atrophy of distal leg muscles.

An arteriovenous malformation is a disruption of the normal vascular pattern in which arteries or arterioles connect directly to the venous collection system, bypassing any capillary bed. This term refers to an arteriovenous malformation located in the optic nerve.

During normal embryological development, the spinal cord first occupies the entire length of the vertebral column but goes on to assume a position at the level of L1 due to differential growth of the conus medullaris and the vertebral column. The filum terminale is a slender, threadlike structure that remains after the normal regression of the distal embryonic spinal cord and attaches the spinal cord to the coccyx. A tethered cord results if there is a thickened rope-like filum terminale which anchors the cord at the level of L2 or below, potentially causing neurologic signs owing to abnormal tension on the spinal cord.
A perinephric abscess is a collection of suppurative material in the perinephric space (i.e., the connective and adipose tissues surrounding the kidney).
Any deviation from the normal concentration of valine in the cerebrospinal fluid.
A type of vitreoretinal degeneration with manifestations that are concentrated at the periphery of the retina.
One or more brown punctate macules on the skin of the genitalia.

A lower midline facial cleft, also known as the median mandibular cleft. It is a rare anomaly, which may be limited to a defect in the soft tissue of the lower lip. However, in the more severe form, it may extend into the bony mandibular symphysis.

Persistence of the hyaloid artery, which is the embryonic artery that runs from the optic disk to the posterior lens capsule may persist; the site of attachment may form an opacity. The hyaloid artery is a branch of the ophthalmic artery, and usually regresses completely before birth.
Failure to develop of the small intestine.
Muscular projections that protrude into the lumen of the bladder, criss-crossing the walls of the bladder on its inner surface.
Trapping and compression of the rotator cuff tendons during shoulder movements.

Leukoplakia is a precancerous dermatosis of mucous membranes analogous Leukoplakia is basically a chronic inflammatory hypertrophy in which anaplasia and malignant dyskeratosis may develop and subsequently advance to an invasive squamous cell cancer. The clinical diagnosis of primary anal leukoplakia is indicated by single or multiple slightly raised,irregular, marginated, grayish-white keratinized' patches in the anal canal. Tissue biopsy is necessary for confirmation.
A type of stenosis of the external auditory meatus in which the opening of the external auditory meatus appears as a vertical slit.
Deterioration or loss of the tissues of the cochlea.

Abnormally short time to coagulation in the prothrombin time test, which is a measure of the extrinsic pathway of coagulation. The results of the prothrombin time test are often expressed in terms of the International normalized ratio (INR), which is calculated as a ratio of the patient's prothrombin time (PT) to a control PT standardized for the potency of the thromboplastin reagent developed by the World Health Organization (WHO) using the formula: INR is equal to Patient PT divided by Control PT.
Underdeveloped, small right heart atrium.
Absence of the middle ear ossicles, malleus, incus, and stapes.

Infection with staphylococcus aureus resistant to the antibiotic methicillin (MRSA). MRSA can infect any individual but is more common among hospitalized patients, and can also occur as an opportunistic infection.
A congenital underdevelopment (aplasia or hypoplasia) of the pancreas.
Epidermal naevi are due to an overgrowth of the epidermis and may be present at birth (50%) or develop during childhood.
Abnormal decussation of the visual pathways, typically identified using visual evoked potentials (VEP) (asymmetrical distribution of the VEP over the posterior scalp).
A broad (120 ms or longer in duration) and bifid P-wave in EKG lead II.
Increased concentration of methylmalonic acid in the blood.
A decrease in high molecular weight von Willebrand factor multimers.
Sudden, repetitive, nonrhythmic motor movements (spasms), involving the eyes and muscles of the face.
Sensorineural hearing impairment with childhood onset.

A congenital malformation of the outflow tract of the heart. Conotruncal defects are thought to result from a disturbance of the outflow tract of the embryonic heart, and comprise truncus arteriosus, tetralogy of Fallot, interrupted aortic arch, transposition of the great arteries, and double outlet right ventricle.
Hypersensitivity in form of an adverse immune reaction against animal dander.
An abnormal increase in the size of the kidney.
Eccentric fixation in which the angle of eccentricity equals the objective angle of deviation.
A diminution in the amplitude (strength) of the pulse such that the examiner has difficulty feeling the pulse.
Unlocalized atrophy of the brain with decreased total brain matter volume and increased ventricular size.
A tendency towards rising very late in the morning and going to bed late at night.

A facial appearance characteristic of myopathic conditions. The face appears expressionless with sunken cheeks, bilateral ptosis, and inability to elevate the corners of the mouth, due to muscle weakness.
Increased susceptibility to herpesvirus, as manifested by recurrent episodes of herpesvirus.
Enlargement of the diameter (cross-section) of a coronary artery as defined by a focal dilation of a segment at least 1.5 times larger than the reference vessel.
A type of holoprosencephaly in which the left and right frontal and parietal lobes are fused and the interhemispheric fissure is only present posteriorly.

A type of focal motor seizure characterized by a sudden interruption in normal tonic muscle activity lasting 500 ms or less, without evidence of preceding myoclonus as the initial semiological manifestation. The interruption in muscle tone is briefer than seen in a focal atonic seizure.
An abnormal decrease in ornithine in the blood.
A sensation of tightness in a toe joint when attempting to move it, especially after a period of inactivity.
A reduction in the number of corneal endothelial cells.
A ureterocele is a congenital saccular dilatation of the distal segment of the ureter.
Marked widening of the major bronchi that may be predispose to chronic respiratory tract infection.
A displacement or misalignment of the humerus with respect to the other bones of the should joint. Note that a subluxation is a partial dislocation.
Zonular cataracts are defined to be cataracts that affect specific regions of the lens.
Rubral tremor is characterized by a slow coarse tremor at rest that is exacerbated by postural adjustments and by guided voluntary movements.
Direction of the U wave opposite to the T wave (i.e., below baseline) in leads with upright T waves.
Any structural anomaly of the mitral valve.
Generalized tonic-clonic seizures on awakening are a form of Generalized tonic-clonic seizures that occur upon awaking.
A congenital deformity characterized by a dorsiflexed, inverted, and adducted foot, i.e., a combination of talipes calcaneus and talipes varus.
Connection of the right atrium to the left ventricle and of the left atrium to the right ventricle in a biventricular heart.
A type of supraventricular tachycardia in which the atria are the principal site of electrophysiologic disturbance.
An abnormality of an external carotid artery.
The presence of varices (enlarged and convoluted blood vessels) in the colon.
Absence of neurologic reflexes such as the knee-jerk reaction.
Paralysis of both the extrinsic and intrinsic ocular muscles.
Feeding problem necessitating nasogastric tube feeding.
Abnormality of the absorption of fat from the gastrointestinal tract.
Congenital absence of the lumen of the larynx.
Any deviation from the normal concentration of isoleucine in the blood circulation.

An abnormal increase of bone mineral density, that is, of the amount of matter per cubic centimeter of bones which is often referred to as osteosclerosis. Osteosclerosis can be detected on radiological examination as an increased whiteness (density) of affected bones.
An abnormally wavy surface or edge of the clavicles.
Any anomaly of the S wave, which is the third component of the QRS wave complex. The S wave signifies the final depolarization of the ventricles at the base of the heart.

Hypoglycosylation of alpha-dystroglycan with O-mannosyl glycans. Alpha-dystroglycan is a functional target of O-mannosyl glycosylation and functional glycosylation of alpha-DG is essential in its interaction with the extracellular matrix.
Any structural anomaly of the principal vein draining blood from the lower portion of the body.
Decreased width of the bony bridge of the nose.
A structural anomaly of the mucous lining of the large intestine.
Discontinuity in the convexity of the inferior margin of the lobe.
Abnormal difficulty in staying asleep. Affected individuals tend to wake up at night and have difficulty returning to sleep.
A form of hyperaldosteronism caused by abnormally increased renin levels.
A nonspecific term referring to disease or damage of the kidneys.
Loss of previously present motor (i.e., movement) abilities.
The presence of excessive fibrous connective tissue in the muscularis propria of the intestine. Fibrosis is a reparative or reactive process.
Abnormal response to ristocetin as manifested by reduced or lacking aggregation of platelets upon addition of ristocetin.
Atrophy of the kidney.

A developmental structural anomaly of the stalk-like part of the brain that comprises the midbrain (aka mesencephalon), the pons (aka pons Varolii), and the medulla oblongata, and connects the cerebral hemispheres with the cervical spinal cord.
A decrease in the level of lactate in the brain identified by magnetic resonance spectroscopy (MRS).
Forward protrusion of the glabella.
A partial or complete breakage of the clavicle bone.
Antihelix protrusion directed more anteriorly than laterally, forming a shelf overlying the posterior concha.
Best corrected visual acuity worse than 1.90 logMAR (roughly 20/1590).
An abnormality of the aryepiglottic fold.
A type of anemia characterized by an abnormally low concentration of hemoglobin in the erythrocytes and lower than normal size of the erythrocytes.
An increased amount of carnosine in the blood.

A focal cognitive seizure involves an alteration in a cognitive function (which can be a deficit or a positive phenomenon such as forced thought), which occurs at seizure onset. To be classified as a focal cognitive seizure, the change in cognitive function should be specific and out of proportion to other relatively unimpaired aspects of cognition, because all cognition is impaired in a focal impaired awareness seizure.
The presence of cartilage cells (chondrocytes) that are substantially increased in size and contain more than one nucleus and are located within the resting zone of the epiphyseal cartilage.
Underdeveloped, small left heart atrium
Disruption of the epithelial layer of the cornea with involvement of the underlying stroma.
Lack or loss of the soft tissues between the zygomata and mandible.
A specific combination of heart defects with a primum atrial septal defect, cleft anterior mitral valve leaflet, and inlet ventricular defect. There is one valve annulus and two valve orifices.
Any deviation from the normal concentration of alanine in the cerebrospinal fluid.
Atrial septal defect (ASD) is a congenital abnormality of the interatrial septum that enables blood flow between the left and right atria via the interatrial septum.
A conical projection of the anterior or posterior surface of the lens, occurring as a developmental anomaly.
Photosensitivity of the skin occurring early in life.
An increase in the level of glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase in a dried blood spot.
Abnormal tortuous (i.e., twisted) form of the aorta.
Paralysis of the external ocular muscles.
A plaque (a solid, raised, plateau-like (flat-topped) lesion greater than 1 cm in diameter) with a red or reddish color often associated with inflammation or irritation.

Flesh-colored or yellowish papules, 2 mm or larger, that are responses to internal mechanical pressure and weakness in the connective tissue in the dermis, appear commonly over the medial aspect of the heel, but in some cases on the wrists. They are thought to represent herniations of adipose tissue through the plantar fascia retinaculum.

In response to the spring sun distinct inflamed reddened skin develops on the ears, nose, cheeks, fingers, backs of the hands, and the lower arms, on which blisters with serous or hemorrhagic content develop. These dry out with the formation of a blackish scab. After shedding of the scab, depressed, varioliform, often hypopigmented scars remain. In addition, hyper- and hypopigmentation are present together, resulting in a polymorphous skin presentation.
Abnormal response to thromboxane as manifested by reduced or lacking aggregation of platelets upon addition of thromboxane A2 receptor agonists.
A type of hemolytic anemia in which the Coombs test is positive.
Increased susceptibility to infection by gram-negative bacteria, as manifested by a medical history of repeated or frequent infections by these agents.

Abnormal function of the renal tubule. The basic functional unit of the kidney, the nephron, consists of a renal corpuscle attached to a renal tubule, with roughly 0.8 to 1.5 nephrons per adult kidney. The functions of the renal tubule include reabsorption of water, electrolytes, glucose, and amino acids and secretion of substances such as uric acid.
Angiofibroma consist of many often dilated vessels.
Excessive, increased hair growth located in the sacral region.
An increased concentration of the BB isoform of creatine kinase in the blood circulation.
Ovarian mucinous neoplasms consist of borderline tumors (tumors of low malignant potential, or LMP tumors), intraepithelial (non-invasive) carcinoma, and invasive carcinoma.
The presence of a malformed cochlea.
Decreased activity of coagulation factor V.

There is a paramedian frontal encephalocele and a soft tissue cleft that passes medial to an intact eyebrow. The frontal bone shows a paramedian bony cleft with an associated encephalocele. The olfactory groove, cribriform plate, and ethmoid sinus are all increased in transverse diameter, resulting in hypertelorism. The cleft extends medially to the undisturbed eyebrow to end in a short paramedian frontal widow's peak. The bony cleft begins in the region of the nasal bone and extends superiorly through the full height of the frontal bone. Posteriorly, the cleft extends through the cribriform plate and ethmoid sinus as far as the lesser wing and body of the sphenoid. The pterygoid processes are anatomically normal, but they are displaced laterally from the midline on the cleft side. There is orbital hypertelorism below and asymmetry of the floor of the anterior cranial fossa above.

Atrioventricular (AV) dissociation is present if the atria and the ventricles are under the control of two separate pacemakers. AV dissociation can occur in the absence of a primary AV conduction disturbance.
Overshoot of downward saccadic eye movements.
An abnormality of the epididymis.
An increase in the concentration of bile acid in the blood.

Anatomic features of unbalanced atrioventricular septal defect (AVSD) include varying amounts of ventricular hypoplasia, as well as malalignment of the atrioventricular junction. In complete AVSD, the common AV valve can be situated either equally over the right and left ventricles (balanced) or unequally over the ventricles (unbalanced).
Abnormal fat accumulation in the kidneys.
Marked widening of the trachea.
A spasm (involuntary contraction) of the vocal cords that can make it difficult to speak or breathe.
An abnormal gyral pattern characterized by abnormalities of sulcal depth or orientation and a thickened cortex intermediate between pachygyria and polymicrogyria.
An anomaly of the addition of mannose to N-linked glycans.
The nostrils (the paired channels of the nose) are not present.
An appetite for and the persistent ingestion of non-food substances such as clay. In order to diagnose pica, this behavior must have persisted over a period of at least one month.
Aplasia (congenital absence) of the olfactory tract, which causes anosmia, a complete loss of the sense of smell.
An abnormality of the xiphoid process of the sternum.
Severe reduction of the ability to see defined as visual acuity less than 6/60 (20/200 in US notation; 0.1 in decimal notation) but at least 3/60 (20/400 in US notation; 0.05 in decimal notation).
A decrease in the level of glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase in a dried blood spot.
A type of cardiac arrhythmia with premature atrial contractions or beats caused by signals originating from ectopic atrial sites.

With left or right cardiac isomerism in a biventricular, the atrioventricular connections are perforce ambiguous, in that one of the connections is concordant (e.g., right-sided morphologic right atrium connected to a morphologic right ventricle) and one of the connections is discordant (e.g., left-sided morphologic right atrium connected to a morphologic left ventricle).
An abnormal narrowing of the lumbar spinal canal.
An anomaly of the wave-like muscle contractions of the digestive tract.
Increased susceptibility to mycobacterial infections, as manifested by recurrent episodes of mycobacterial infection.

A tram-track sign is composed of two enhancing areas of tumor separated from each other by the negative defect of the optic nerve. It is seen on contrast-enhanced CT scan and MRI images, in optic nerve sheath meningioma. The sign helps distinguish between optic nerve sheath meningioma and optic glioma. Optic glioma arises from glial cells within the optic nerve and there is no clear separation between the nerve and the tumor; hence the tram-track sign is not seen in optic gliomas. Calcification may be seen in optic nerve sheath meningiomas in 20-50% of cases and hence the tram-track sign may be seen on nonenhanced CT scan images as a linear calcification around the nerve, but this is less common.
Adrenal insufficiency secondary to a defect in the ACTH receptor.

A form of gray matter heterotopia were the mislocalized gray matter is typically located periventricularly, also sometimes called subependymal heterotopia. Periventricular means beside the ventricles. This is by far the most common location for heterotopia. Subependymal heterotopia present in a wide array of variations. There can be a small single node or a large number of nodes, can exist on either or both sides of the brain at any point along the higher ventricle margins, can be small or large, single or multiple, and can form a small node or a large wavy or curved mass.

A form of anomalous eating behavior characterized by binge eating is followed by self-induced vomiting or other compensatory behavior intended to prevent weight gain (purging, fasting or exercising or a combination of these).
An abnormality of the formation and mineralization of an epiphysis.
Immunohistochemistry shows complete lack of beta sarcoglycan protein in the muscle biopsy.
A severe form of lactic acidemia.
Hypergranulosis is an increased thickness of the stratum granulosum.
The presence of calculi (stones) in the kidneys.
Flattening instead of curving or rounded superior helix, allowing the superior helix to run more horizontally than usual.
An increased susceptibility to Aspergillus infections, as manifested by a history of recurrent episodes of Aspergillus infections.
Distance from nasion to subnasale more than two standard deviations above the mean, or alternatively, an apparently increased length from the nasal root to the nasal base.
Reduction of goal-directed behaviors linked to the impairment in frontal executive functions (planning of an action for example).

Reduced level of one or more components of the the terminal membrane attack complex (MAC) portion of complement, which represents the lytic, pore-forming part of the system. The MAC comprises seven components: C5b, C6, C7, C8 (a heterotrimer composed of C8alpha, C8beta and C8gamma) and multiple copies of C9.
Formation of an anuclear keratin layer
A fluid filled sac in the kidney.
Lack of contraction of abdominal muscles in the quadrant of the abdomen that is stimulated by scraping the skin tangential to or toward the umbilicus.
A murmur that occurs in the middle of the diastolic phase.
Pierre Robin malformation is a sequence of developmental malformations characterized by micrognathia (mandibular hypoplasia), glossoptosis and cleft palate.
Abnormal response to thrombin or thrombin mimetics as manifested by reduced or lacking aggregation of platelets upon addition of thrombin (or thrombin mimetics).
An increase in the combined thickness of the intima and media of the carotid artery.
An abnormality in the reflexive contraction of the middle-ear muscles in response to sound stimulation.
A small pupil (typically diameter less than 2 mm) that dilates poorly or not at all in response to topically administered mydriatic drugs.
A type of onion bulb formation prominently affecting the area of the basal lamina.

Usually, Lymphoycytes make up less than 15% of all cells found in the bronchoalveloar lavage fluid. This elevated cell proportion can be induced by virus or drugs, or is associated with specific diseases.
The presence of a mild form of sensorineural hearing impairment.
Abnormal flatness (decreased height) of epiphyses.
Impaired function of the exocrine pancreas associated with a reduced ability to digest foods because of lack of digestive enzymes.
Saccular dilatation of the terminal bronchioles.
Inaccurate saccades (rapid movement of the eye between fixation points) in the horizontal direction.
Localized or generalized increased genital pigmentation.
An increased quantity of earwax.
A compression or resistance upon the bladder outflow channel at any location from the bladder neck to urethral meatus, which usually causes lower urinary tract symptoms (LUTS).
A cleft of the optic nerve that extends inferiorly.

Restrictive left ventricular physiology is characterized by a pattern of ventricular filling in which increased stiffness of the myocardium causes ventricular pressure to rise precipitously with only small increases in volume, defined as restrictive ventricular physiology in the presence of normal or reduced diastolic volumes (of one or both ventricles), normal or reduced systolic volumes, and normal ventricular wall thickness.
A decreased amount of carnosine in bood.
Immunohistochemistry shows complete lack of gamma sarcoglycan protein in the muscle biopsy.
Abnormally increased movement at the junction between the first cervical (atlas) and the second cervical (axis) vertebrae as a result of either a bony or ligamentous anomaly.
An excessive desire to eat salt (sodium chloride) or salty foods.

This sign represents thickening and enhancement of the dura mater in continuity with a mass, which on MR images, gives the appearance of a tail arising from the mass. The dural tail is thought to represent reactive change; however, it may also be due to tumor invasion. Three criteria need to be met for a positive dural tail sign: the tail should be seen on two successive images through the tumor, it should taper away from the tumor, and it must enhance more than the tumor.
Nystagmus consisting of horizontal to-and-fro eye movements.

Engagement in dangerous, risky, and potentially self-damaging activities, unnecessarily and without regard to consequences; lack of concern for one's limitations and denial of the reality of personal danger.
A complete or partial duplication of the tragus; expected to lie anterior to the normal tragus.
A murmur that occurs in the latter phase of systole.
Hyperplasia of the pancreas.
A type of epidermal acanthosis characterized by a jagged (sawtooth) appearance of the rete ridges of the epidermis.

In this case the right ventricle is more muscular than normal, causing a characteristic boot-shaped (coeur-en-sabot) appearance as seen on anterior- posterior chest x-rays. Right ventricular hypertrophy is commonly associated with any form of right ventricular outflow obstruction or pulmonary hypertension, which may in turn owe its origin to left-sided disease. The echocardiographic signs are thickening of the anterior right ventricular wall and the septum. Cavity size is usually normal, or slightly enlarged. In many cases there is associated volume overload present due to tricuspid regurgitation, in the absence of this, septal motion is normal.
Any deviation from the normal concentration of lysine in the blood circulation.
Hypersensitivity in form of an adverse immune reaction against insect bites.
A developmental anomaly of the ureter.
An increase in voltage of the PR segment above baseline.
A systolic murmur that begins after S1 and ends before S2, typically with a crescendo-decrescendo pattern.
Decreased activity of coagulation factor IX. Factor IX, which itself is activated by factor Xa or factor VIIa to form factor IXa, activates factor X into factor Xa.

Irregular, small-amplitude myoclonic movements of the hands and/or fingers on keeping outstretched posture (jerky postural tremor). Polyminimyoclonus is stimulus-sensitive and accentuated during voluntary movements. A cortical origin can be demonstrated by back-averaging techniques, and somatosensory evoked potentials (SSEPs) are sometimes giant.
Any deviation from the normal concentration of glutamine amino acids in the cerebrospinal fluid.
A form of lactic acidemia that occurs in relation to stress or infection.
Loss of hair in the occipital region of the scalp with congenital onset.
The presence of developmental dysplasia of the retina.
Abnormal plane of direction of the heart from the base to the apex in the midline. Left sided is normal.
An abnormality of the metencephalon. The metencephalon is the part of the hindbrain that consists of the pons and the cerebellum.
Deviation from normal of the ratio of adenosine triphosphate (ATP) to adenosine diphosphate (ADP) within platelets.
An unusually severe infection by cytomegalovirus.
An accessory (not normally present) muscle bundle in the right ventricle which obstructs the right ventricular outflow tract.
The loss of continuity between the left subclavian artery and the aorta, with persistent connection to the homolateral pulmonary artery through the patent (PDA) or nonpatent ductus arteriosus.

The sacroiliac joint in the bony pelvis connects the sacrum and the ilium of the pelvis, which are joined by strong ligaments. The notch is located directly superior to the joint. This term refers to a reduction in the height of the notch.
A congenital anomaly with lack of part of the pericardium on the lefthand side of the heart.
A delay in the acquisition of the ability to use language to communicate needs, wishes, or thoughts.
Increased susceptibility to enteroviral infections, as manifested by recurrent episodes of enteroviral infection.
Lack of merosin protein in the muscle biopsy.

Reduced bulkiness of the crease or fold of skin running from the lateral margin of the nose, where nasal base meets the skin of the face, to a point just lateral to the corner of the mouth (cheilion or commissure).
Cardiac arrest that would have led to rapid and unexpected death had an intervention not taken place to prevent it.
An anomaly of the glenoid fossa, also known as the glenoid cavity, which is the articular surface of the scapula that articulates with the head of the humerus.
Unilateral atrophy of facial tissues, including muscles, bones and skin.
An abnormal narrowing of the spinal canal related to a reduction in the interpedicular distance (i.e., the distance measured between the pedicles on frontal [coronal] imaging).
A mild form of conductive hearing impairment.
Sparseness of the body hair.
Progressive spinal muscular atrophy, i.e., muscular weakness and atrophy related to loss of the motor neurons of the spinal cord and brainstem.
The presence of an abnormally large pelvis.
Abnormally narrow nasal septum.
Any deviation from the normal concentration of glutamic acid in the cerebrospinal fluid.

A specific combination of heart defects with a primum atrial septal defect, cleft anterior mitral valve leaflet, and an inlet ventricular septal defect. There are two valve annuli and two valve orifices.
Positioning of the nasal septum to the right or left in contrast to the normal midline position of the nasal septum.
Hypersensitivity in form of an adverse immune reaction against insect venom.
Increased susceptibility to chicken pox, as manifested by recurrent episodes of chicken pox.
A type of short-limbed dwarfism that is manifest beginning in the neonatal period.
Uncontrolled episodes of crying, without apparent motivating stimuli.
Buildups of minerals that form in the urinary bladder.
A segmental pattern of demyelination and regeneration (remyelination) affecting peripheral nerves.
No pericardium over the diaphragmatic surface of the heart. It is a congenital defect, not the result of a pericardectomy. Pericardium is present on other parts of the heart.
Violaceous papules overlying the dorsal and lateral aspects of the metacarpophalangeal and proximal interphalangeal joints.
A type of persistance of the hyaloid vascular system associated with a retrolental mass that may lead to fetal cataract.
A structural anomaly of the olfactory lobe, the structure within the brain that receives neural input from the nasal cavity and thereby processes the sense of smell.
The presence of autoantibodies in the serum that react against proteins predominantly expressed in perinuclear region of neutrophils.
An infection with nontuberculous mycobacteria that affects multiple body sites. Such infections can occur in individuals with immune disease.
An decrease in the level of choline-containing compounds in the brain identified by magnetic resonance spectroscopy (MRS).
Oxygen saturation less than 95% on exertion or arterial partial pressure of oxygen falling by more than 1kPa.

A nodular pattern is characterised on pulmonary high-resolution computed tomography by the presence of numerous rounded opacities that range from 2 mm to 1 cm in diameter, with micronodules defined as smaller than 3 mm in diameter.
A reduction in the thickness of the outer shell (cortex) of foot bones.
A hole (perforation) in the wall of the rectum.
An abnormal narrowing of the cervical spinal canal.
An increased concentration of histidine in the blood.
An anomaly of the arch of aorta.

An abnormal forward-flexed posture e.g. forward flexion of the spine, which is noticeable when standing or walking but disappears when lying down. It is becoming an increasingly recognized feature of Parkinson's disease and dystonic disorders.

A functional anomaly of the superior rectus muscle, an extraocular muscle that is innervated by the superior division of the oculomotor nerve, and whose primary function is the elevation of the globe.
The presence in the axillary region (armpit) of an increased number of freckles, small circular spots on the skin that are darker than the surrounding skin because of deposits of melanin.
Abnormal bone tissue formation (ossification) affecting the sacrum.
Crackles that appear at the beginning of inspiration and end before mid-inspiration.
Aortic dissection refers to a tear in the intimal layer of the aorta causing a separation between the intima and the medial layers of the aorta.
Enlarged and tortuous veins.

This midline cranial cleft usually occurs with a midline facial cleft that completes a median craniofacial dysraphia. A broad nasal root and bifid nose are associated with orbital hypertelorism and a median frontal encephalocele. The frontal bone abnormality varies from a minor flattening to a large midline defect. There is an increased distance between the olfactory grooves. The crista galli is widened, duplicated, or in some cases absent. Marked inferior prolapse of the enlarged ethmoid bone occurs with orbital hypertelorism. The severe orbital hypertelorism is associated with a broad flattening of the glabella and extreme lateral displacement of the inner canthi. The periorbita, including the eyelids and eyebrows, are otherwise normal. A long midline projection of the frontal hairline marks the superior extent of the soft tissue features of this midline cranial cleft. The median frontal defect delineates the region through which the frontal encephalocele herniates. The lateral segments of the frontal bone sweep upward from the region of the intact glabella and are flattened laterally. No pneumatization of the frontal sinus is evident. The crista galli and the perpendicular plate of the ethmoid are bifid. Just as the ethmoid, including the cribriform plate, is widened and caudally displaced, the sphenoid sinus is broadened and extensively, but symmetrically pneumatized. The lateral rotation of the greater and lesser wings of the sphenoid results in a relative shortening of the anteroposterior dimension of the middle cranial fossa. The floor of the anterior cranial fossa is upslanting from its medial aspect to its lateral aspect, with a harlequin appearance on the coronal scan.
Longstanding metabolic acidosis.
An aberrant thyroid gland or Ectopic thyroid located at the base of the tongue, just posterior to the foramen cecum as a result of a failure of the thyroid to descend.
Lack of improvement of muscle strength in response to administration of an acetylcholine esterase inhibitor.
Pruritus is an itch or a sensation that makes a person want to scratch. This term refers to an abnormally increased sensation of itching over the palm(s) of the hand.
Duplication of the spinal cord.
Unusual gonadal development in a person with a 46,XY male karyotype, leading to a more female sex differentiation.
An abnormaltiy of the rectum, the final segment of the large intestine that stores solid waste until it passes through the anus.

Reluctance or refusal of a child to be breastfed or eat, manifested as gagging, vomiting, turning head away from food, or avoidance of sensation in or around the mouth (i.e. toothbrushing or face-washing).
Persistent abnormal dilatation of the bronchi owing to localized and irreversible destruction and widening of the large airways.
A reduction in the concentration of 12-HETE in the blood circulation, a metabolite of arachidonic acid.
A morphological abnormality of the optic disc, i.e., of the portion of the optic nerve clinically visible on fundoscopic examination.
Increased pigmentation of the fundus
Increased height of the tragal ridge with a shallow indentation at the apex, giving the appearance of a double peak.
A solid, raised, plateau-like (flat-topped) lesion greater than 1 cm in diameter that is characterized by hardening (sclerosis) of the affected skin area (related to collagen thickening).
Increased susceptibility to staphylococcal infections, as manifested by recurrent episodes of staphylococcal infections.

The so-called crazy paving pattern is characterised on HRCT by the presence of thickened interlobular septae and intralobular lines superimposed on a background of ground-glass opacity, resembling irregularly shaped paving stones.

A form of focal dystonia affecting the face and especially the jaw that is induced by the act of speaking. It is an involuntary contraction of the masticatory muscles, resulting in dysarthria or dysphagia.
A reduced sense of touch (tactile sensation). This is usually tested with a wisp of cotton or a fine camel's hair brush, by asking patients to say 'now' each time they feel the stimulus.
The presence of arthrosis, i.e., of degenerative joint disease, affecting the cervical vertebral column.
An anomaly of the addition of fucose sugar units to O-linked glycans.
Abnormal plane of direction of the heart from the base to the apex towards the right. Left sided is normal.

A ventircular escape rhythm occurs whenever higher-lever pacemakers in AV junction or sinus node fail to control ventricular activation. Escape rate is usually 20-40 bpm, often associated with broad QRS complexes (at least 120 ms).
An abnormality of the urethra, i.e., of the tube which connects the urinary bladder to the outside of the body.
Any deviation from the normal concentration of arginine in the blood circulation.
Reduced transparency of the stroma of cornea.
Localized or generalized decreased genital pigmentation.
Blockage of the external auditory canal by a buildup of earwax.
Punding is a stereotypical motor behavior characterized by an intense fascination with repetitive, excessive and non-goal oriented handling, and examining of objects.
A small tear in the thin, moist tissue (mucosa) that lines the anus. It appears as a crack or slit in the mucous membrane of the anus.
A cataract that affects the region of the lens directly beneath the capsule of the lens.
Any structural anomaly of the saccule of the vestibule. The saccule is the otolith organ that senses motions in the sagittal plane (i.e., up-down movement).
Immunohistochemistry reveals reduced gamma sarcoglycan protein in the muscle biopsy.

Unusual regions of densely packed membranous tubules known as tubular aggregates which present as membranous inclusions, derived from membranes of sarcoplasmic reticulum and mitochondria, containing miscellaneous proteins with a variety of enzymatic activities.
Congenital lack of development of the muscles, which are then replaced by a mixture of dense fat and fibrous tissue.
Unilateral underdevelopment of the facial tissues, including muscles and bones.
Increased time for the PR interval (beginning of the P wave to the beginning of the QRS complex).
Episodes of muscle weakness associated with reduced levels of potassium in the blood.

Patchy (irregular) changes in bone mineral density. These changes can either be patchy reduction or increase of mineral density as seen on x-rays. Depending on the pathomechanism and the underlying disease, these changes can either appear solely as reduction or increase or as a combination of both (patches of bone showing an increased density while others are affected by reduction of mineral density).
The presence of two distinct odontoid processes. The odontoid process, also known as the dens of the axis, is a protuberance of the C2 vertebral body around which the first vertebra rotates.
A reduced level of the complement component C4 in the circulation.
Reduced strength of the masseter muscle, whose primary function is to elevate the mandible and thereby raise the mandible towards the maxilla, closing the jaw.
Reduction in thickness of the skin, generally associated with a loss of suppleness and elasticity of the skin.
A reduced amount of merosin in muscle fibers. This feature is usually assessed by immunohistochemical examination of muscle biopsy tissue.

Tendon reflexes that are noticeably more active than usual (conventionally denoted 3+ on clinical examination). Brisk reflexes may or may not indicate a neurological lesion. They are distinguished from hyperreflexia by the fact that hyerreflexia is characterized by hyperactive repeating (clonic) reflexes, which are considered to be always abnormal.
A type of insomnia characterized by waking up (too) early in the morning.
Presence of all the normal ear components and the median longitudinal length more than two standard deviations below the mean.
Abnormal thickening of the cortex of long bones.
Transient, non-scarring hair loss and preservation of the hair follicle located in in well-defined patches.
A tumor that originates in cells from the primitive neural crest. This group of tumors is characteirzed by the presence of primitive cells with elements of neuronal and/or glial differentiation.
An abnormal morphology of the olfactory bulb (bulbus olfactorius), which is involved in olfaction, i.e. the sense of smell.
Abnormally reduced amount of delta sarcoglycan in muscle.
Unusual gonadal development in a person with a 46,XY male karyotype, leading to an unassigned sex differentiation.
A form of heterotopia were the mislocalized gray matter is located deep within the white matter.
An abnormality of the common carotid arteries, which provide the arterial supply to the head and neck and give rise to the internal carotid artery and the external carotid artery.
An inversion of the T-wave (which is normally positive).
Any structural anomaly of the principal vein draining blood from the upper portion of the body and delivering it to the right ventricle of the heart.
Adhesions between the iris and the cornea.
Interalar distance more than two standard deviations above the mean for age, i.e., an apparently increased width of the nasal base and alae.
An abnormality of the third ventricle.

Usually, Neutrophils make up less than 3% of all cells found in the broncho-alveloar lavage fluid. In children, standard value of neutrophils is higher depending on their age (children under the age of 5 show a maximum value of 10%). This elevated cell proportion is a sign for acute and chronic infections (HP:0012387, HP:0006538) and can be associated to specific diseases.
An increase in the level of glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase in leukocytes.
P wave below instead of above the baseline. P-wave inversion in the inferior leads may indicate a non-sinus origin of the P waves.
An abnormality in which the cardiac ventricles depolarize too early as a result of an abnormality of cardiac conduction pathways such as an accessory pathway.
Increased concentration of ornithine in the blood.

A type of focal motor seizure characterized by difficulty with articulation of speech, due to impaired coordination of muscles involved in speech sound production as the initial semiological manifestation. Receptive and expressive language functions are intact, however speech is poorly articulated and is less intelligible.

An entrapment neuropathy of the suprascapular nerve, presenting with shoulder weakness confined to the supraspinatus muscle (this muscle initiates shoulder abduction) or to the infraspinatus (this muscle externally rotates the arm), as well as with pain in the posterior part of the shoulder and upper periscapular region.
Overgrowth of the stratum corneum characterized by flesh-coloured or slightly pigmented smooth or warty papules on the upper surface of hands and feet.

Atrophy of the interosseus muscles (including the palmar interossei that lie on the anterior aspect of the metacarpals, the dorsal interosseus muscles of the hand, which lie between the intercarpals, the plantar interosseus muscles, which lie underneath the metatarsal bones, and the dorsal interossei, which are located between the metatarsal bones.
Reduced number or density of pubic hair.
An abnormality of the pulmonary situs, i.e., of the sidedness of the morphological right and left lungs, in which both lungs have the morphology of a right lung.
Any deviation from the normal concentration of serine in the cerebrospinal fluid.

A reduction in the level of performance of the kidneys in areas of function comprising the concentration of urine, removal of wastes, the maintenance of electrolyte balance, homeostasis of blood pressure, and calcium metabolism.
A severe form of sensorineural hearing impairment.
Loss of the outer layer of the epidermis in large, scale-like flakes localized to the palm of the hand and the sole of the foot.

Myoclonic absence seizure is a type of generalized non-motor (absence) seizure characterised by an interruption of ongoing activities, a blank stare and rhythmic three-per-second myoclonic movements, causing ratcheting abduction of the upper limbs leading to progressive arm elevation, and associated with 3 Hz generalized spike-wave discharges on the electroencephalogram. Duration is typically 10-60 s. Whilst impairment of consciousness may not be obvious the ILAE classified this seizure as a generalized non-motor seizure in 2017.
A state of sudden and severe confusion.
Abnormal result of a test designed to test an individual's central and peripheral vision by determining the ability of the individual to perceive objects at differing locations of the visual field.
Co-occurrence of reticular and micronodular patterns on pulmonary high-resolution computed tomography.
Crackles that appear any time after the beginning of inspiration and last till the end of inspiration.
A reduction in the concentration of bile acid in the blood.
Impairment of expressive language and relative preservation of receptive language abilities. That is, the patient understands language (speech, writing) but cannot express it.
Degeneration (wear and tear) of the articular cartilage of the neck joints.
Failure of the tricuspid valve to close sufficiently upon contraction of the right ventricle, causing blood to regurgitate (flow backward) into the right atrium.

A developmental defect of the sacrum characterized by partial or disordered development of the sacrum in which portions of the sacrum, which normally is formed by fusion of five sacral vertebrae S1-S5, fail to form or fail to form normally.
A type of focal motor seizure in which awareness is partially or fully impaired at some point during the seizure.
A decreased concentration of glucose in the blood associated with a reduced concentration of ketone bodies.
A heart murmur that occurs during the entire systolic phase from S1 to S2.
A form of hemolytic anemia that can be triggered by cold temperatures.

Lack of response to scratching of the skin of the medial thigh, which in males normally elicits a brisk, short elevation of the ipsilateral testis, a phenomenon that is referred to as the cremaster reflex.

Abnormal origin of the right subclavian artery from the descending aorta. The right subclavian artery normally arises from the brachiocephalic trunk, which divides into the right common carotid artery and right subclavian artery.
An unusually severe Epstein Barr virus (EBV) infection.
A notch or cleft of the retina.
Absence of menses for an interval of time equivalent to a total of more than (or equal to) 3 previous cycles or 6 months.
Disturbance in the atrial activation that is caused by transient failure of impulse conduction from the sinoatrial node to the cardiac atria.
An autonomic seizure is a type of focal non-motor seizure characterized by alteration of autonomic nervous system function as the initial semiological feature.
Permanent indentation on the posteromedial aspect of the helix that may be sharply or indistinctly delineated.
Underdevelopment of the helix, i.e., of the outer rim of the pinna.
A type of status epilepticus without prominent motor symptoms in the absence of coma.
Developmental hypoplasia of the antihelix.
A skin texture that is unusually soft (and may feel silky), and has a malleable consistency resembling that of dough.
Joint pain affecting the hip.
Immunohistochemistry reveals reduced beta sarcoglycan protein in the muscle biopsy.
A morphological anomaly of the nasal cartilage.
A type of status epilepticus without prominent motor symptoms and in the presence of coma.
Cell death (necrosis) affecting one or more parts of the kidney.
Any deviation from the normal concentration of glycine in the cerebrospinal fluid.
An inability to digest starch.
Abnormal narrowing of the coronary artery.
A complex congenital heart defect in which the aorta arises from the morphologic right ventricle and the pulmonary artery arises from the morphologic left ventricle.
The absence of the normal curvature of the vertebral column.

Increased time to coagulation in the prothrombin time test, which is a measure of the extrinsic pathway of coagulation. The results of the prothrombin time test are often expressed in terms of the International normalized ratio (INR), which is calculated as a ratio of the patient's prothrombin time (PT) to a control PT standardized for the potency of the thromboplastin reagent developed by the World Health Organization (WHO) using the formula: INR is equal to Patient PT divided by Control PT.
A papule with the same color as the surrounding skin.
An anomaly of the addition of sialic acids to N-linked glycans.
A structural anomaly of the adjacent structures (i.e., adnexa) of the eye, defined as the lacrimal apparatus, the extraocular muscles and the eyelids, eyelashes, eyebrows and the conjunctiva.

A sudden episode of intense fear in a situation in which there is no danger or apparent cause. The panic attack is accompanied by symptoms such as palpitations, sweating and chills or hot flushes. There may be a sensation of dyspnea (being out of breath), chest pain, or abdominal distress. Some individuals with panic attacks may experience depersonalization, a fear of going crazy, or a fear of dying.
Excessive, increased hair growth located in the lumbar region.
Muscular hypotonia (abnormally low muscle tone) manifesting in the neonatal period and affecting the entire musculature.
Multiple vesicles distributed in multiple distinct groups consisting of multiple adjacent vesicles.
Weakness of both lower extremities with sparing of the upper extremities. Paraplegia refers to a severe or complete loss of strength, whereas paraparesis refers to a relatively mild loss of strength.
Anterior chamber cells with 16-25 cells in a 1 mm by 1 mm slit beam field, employing adequate light intensity and magnification on a slit lamp.
Any structural abnormality of the vagina.

Aortic valve prolapse can be diagnosed when either or both of the right or non-coronary aortic valve cusps (seen in the cross sectional echocardiographic long axis view) show backward bowing towards the left ventricle beyond a line joining the points of attachment of the aortic valve leaflets to the annulus.
Distance between subnasale and pronasale more than two standard deviations above the mean, or alternatively, an apparently increased anterior protrusion of the nasal tip.
An increase in the amount of glycogen stored in hepatocytes compared to normal.

Any deviation from the normal degree of echogenicity of the liver on sonography. Echogenicity refers to the ability of a tissue to reflect or transmit ultrasound waves in the context of surrounding tissues. Whenever there is an interface of structures with different echogenicities, a visible difference in contrast will be apparent on the screen. Based on echogenicity, a structure can be characterized as hyperechoic (white on the screen), hypoechoic (gray on the screen) and anechoic (black on the screen).
Underdevelopment of a fingernail.
An abnormal reduction in the amount of pigmentation of the iris.
A decreased amount of lamin A/C in muscle tissue. This feature can be shown by immunohistochemistry of Western blotting of muscle tissue.
A posterior embryotoxon is the presence of a prominent and anteriorly displaced line of Schwalbe.
A oval and round, colored (usually medium-to dark brown, reddish brown, or flesh colored) lesion. Typically, a melanocytic nevus is less than 6 mm in diameter, but may be much smaller or larger.
Reduced pigmentation of hair in patches.
A type of hypoplastic anemia with congenital onset.
Bursts of large-amplitude multidirectional saccades without intersaccadic interval
Absence of hair in the anterior midline and/or parietal areas.
Fiber- or rope-like opacities located within the vitreous humor.
Regurgitation of milk through the nose.
An abnormality of the stapes, a stirrup-shaped ossicle in the middle ear.
A transverse linear fissure (crease) in the lobule of the ear.
An increase in the degree of curvature of the cornea compared to normal.
A continuous form of lactic acidemia.

Hyperkeratosis is thickening of the outer layer of the skin, the stratum corneum, which is composed of large, polyhedral, plate-like envelopes filled with keratin which are the dead cells that have migrated up from the stratum granulosum.
Distance from nasion to subnasale more than two standard deviations below the mean, or alternatively, an apparently decreased length from the nasal root to the nasal tip.
The presence of multiple sausage-shaped swellings of the myelin sheath (The Latin tomaculum means sausage).
The presence of developmental dysplasia of the optic nerve.
Flatness of the supraorbital portion of the frontal bones.
A solitary yellow-orange slightly raised plaque typically on scalp or face. The plaque typically thickens and becomes more verrucous or pebbly during childhood.

Cone-shaped epiphyses (also known as coned epiphyses) are epiphyses that invaginate into cupped metaphyses. That is, the epiphysis has a cone-shaped distal extension resulting from increased growth of the central portion of the epiphysis relative to its periphery.
Asymmetry observed in the face of a neonate or infant whose face appears symmetric at rest and asymmetric during crying as the mouth is pulled downward on one side while not moving on the other side.
The presence of degenerative changes of intervertebral disk.
Recurrent episodes of decreased concentration of glucose in the blood.
V-shaped cut (notch) in the middle of the P wave.
Coexistence of two hemicords, at variable levels, causing splaying of the posterior vertebral elements. Results in neurological deficits in lower limb or perineum.
Improvement of muscle strength in response to administration of an acetylcholine esterase inhibitor.
The presence of large spherical melanosomes (1 to 6 micrometer in diameter) in the cytoplasm of melanocytes.
Intermittent episodes of ketoacidosis.
Abnormal levels of interferon gamma measured in the blood circulation.

The sacroiliac joint in the bony pelvis connects the sacrum and the ilium of the pelvis, which are joined by strong ligaments. The notch is located directly superior to the joint. This term refers to a increase in the lateral dimension of the notch.
Degeneration of retinal ganglion cells and their axons.
Abnormal layering of the intestinal muscularis propria into three layers; (1) inner circular; (2) additional oblique; and (3) outer longitudinal layer.

A generalized myoclonic seizure is a type of generalized motor seizure characterised by bilateral, sudden, brief (<100 ms) involuntary single or multiple contraction of muscles or muscle groups of variable topography (axial, proximal limb, distal). Myoclonus is less regularly repetitive and less sustained than is clonus.
A hole between the two bottom chambers (ventricles) of the heart. The defect is centered around the most superior aspect of the ventricular septum.
A kind of hemolytic anemia that is induced by the ingestion of fava beans.
A papule with yellow color.
An abnormality of the spinal dura mater, which is the outermost of the three layers of the meninges surrounding the spinal cord.
Western blot shows complete lack of calpain-3 protein in the muscle biopsy tissue.

Acting on the spur of the moment in response to immediate stimuli; acting on a momentary basis without a plan or consideration of outcomes; difficulty establishing or following plans; a sense of urgency and self-harming behavior under emotional distress.
Accumulation of abnormal amounts of pigment within the trabecular meshwork.
Underdevelopment of the toenail.

A specific combination of heart defects including a primum atrial septal defect and cleft anterior mitral valve leaflet. There is not an inlet ventricular septal defect present. There are two valve annuluses and two valve orifices.

Reduced dimension of the solid part of the kidney (parenchyma, the renal cortex and medulla) as measured from the collecting system (renal calyces and pelvis) to the border of the kidney. This measurement can be performed by measuring the thickness of the parenchyma in computed tomography scans.
Any defect in the valve connecting the heart and the pulmonary artery.
An increase in the number of immune cells in myocardial tissue concentrated in the spaces surrounding blood vessels.
An elevation of alpha-feto protein measured in the amniotic fluid.

A generalized tonic seizure is a type of generalized motor seizure characterised by bilateral limb stiffening or elevation, often with neck stiffening without a subsequent clonic phase. The tonic activity can be a sustained abnormal posture, either in extension or flexion, sometimes accompanied by tremor of the extremities.
Impairment of bile flow due to obstruction in large bile ducts outside the liver.
Weakness or softness of the cartilage in the walls of the bronchial tubes.
A condition in which the skin can be stretched beyond normal, and then returns to its initial position.
Any deviation from the normal circulation of leucine in the blood circulation.
An increase in the length of time required for food to pass through the intestines.
A type of hearing impairment caused by an abnormal functionality of the cochlear nerve with congenital onset.
A type of focal motor seizure (it commences in one hemisphere) involving bilateral muscle groups rapidly at seizure onset.
An abnormality of the Falx cerebri.
Absence of pubic hair.

Generalized clonic seizure is a type of generalized motor seizure characterised by sustained bilateral jerking, either symmetric or asymmetric, that is regularly repetitive and involves the same muscle groups.
A left-right reversal (or "mirror reflection") of the anatomical location of the major thoracic and abdominal organs.
A dissemination viral infection caused by a live attenuated vaccine virus.
An abnormal concentration of potassium.
An abnormality of an alanine metabolic process.
A confined region of lax skin that hangs below the level of the surrounding skin. Histopatholigically, there is a loss of elastic fibers in the dermis of the affected region.
Facial height (length) is more than 2 standard deviations above the mean (objective); or, an apparent increase in the height (length) of the face (subjective).
A urodynamic anomaly characterized by bladder outlet obstruction from detrusor muscle contraction with concomitant involuntary urethral sphincter activation.
Abnormality of the midnasal cavity which includes the cavity between the nares and the choanae.
Anemia characterized by the presence of erythroblasts that are larger than normal (megaloblasts).

A reduction compared to the predicted value of the forced expiratory flow over the middle one-half of the FVC; the average flow from the point at which 25% of the FVC has been exhaled to the point at which 75% of the FVC has been exhaled. Here, the test is performed after the administration of a bronchodilating medication.
An electrocardiographic anomaly in which the ST segment is observed to be located superior to the isoelectric line.
Substantially shortened length of the small intestine as a result of a developmental defect.
The presence of circulating IgG autoantibodies to cardiolipin.
Presenile cataract is a kind of cataract that occurs in early adulthood, that is, at an age that is younger than usual.

Seizures presenting with an emotion or the appearance of having an emotion as an early prominent feature, such as fear, spontaneous joy or euphoria, laughing (gelastic), or crying, (dacrystic). These emotional seizures may occur with or without objective clinical signs of a seizure evident to the observer.

Narrowing of peripheral arteries with reduction of blood flow to the limbs. This feature may be quantified as an ankle-brachial index of less than 0.9, and may be manifested clinically as claudication.

A diagnostic reflex elicited by stimulation of the skin over the surface of the lateral malleolus of the foot. The Chaddock refelx is present if there is extension of one or more or all of the toes with or without fanning of them when the external inframalleolar skin is stimulated. The Chaddock sign, similar to the Babinski sign, is taken to be an indication of disease of the spinocortical (pyramidal) tract.
A structural abnormality of the macula lutea, which is an oval-shaped highly pigmented yellow spot near the center of the retina.
Partial or complete loss of vision in one half of the visual field of one or both eyes.
Repeated episodes of sudden-onset and transient lethargy.
Deposits accumulating between the outer retina and the retinal pigment epithelium.
A well-circumscribed, intensely pruritic, raised wheal (edema of the superficial skin) typically 1 to 2 cm in diameter.
An increased concentration of interleukin-6 in the circulation.
An abnormal connection between a carotid artery and the cavernous sinus.
A deviation from the normal count of alpha granules per thrombocyte.
A comedo in which the top of the pore is not stretched open and thus does not expose the clogged portion (which would appear black), hence the name whitehead.
A type of sideroblastic anemia that is alleviated by pyridoxine (vitamin B-6) treatment.
A collection of clotted blood surrounding the kidney.
Qualitatively abnormal fibrinogen.
An abnormality of the stem of the antihelix, which is the part below the bifurcation of the antihelix into the inferior and superior crura.

An elevation of the level of the enzyme creatine kinase (also known as creatine phosphokinase, CPK; EC 2.7.3.2) in the blood. CPK levels can be elevated in a number of clinical disorders such as myocardial infarction, rhabdomyolysis, and muscular dystrophy.
Muscular hypotonia (abnormally low muscle tone) affecting the musculature of the trunk and with onset in infancy.

Increased concentration of 11-deoxycortisol in the circulation. 11-deoxycorticosterone, which is also known as simply deoxycorticosterone and 21-hydroxyprogesterone, is a steroid hormore that is produces in the adrenals and is a precursor to aldosterone.

A type of ataxia characterized by the impairment of the ability to perform rapidly alternating movements, such as pronating and supinating his or her hand on the dorsum of the other hand as rapidly as possible.

A type of status epilepticus characterized by a prolonged bilateral tonic-clonic seizure, or repeated bilateral tonic-clonic seizures without recovery between.

seeAlso: Tonic-clonic status epilepticus

A type of focal motor seizure characterized by sudden, brief (<100 ms) involuntary single or multiple contraction(s) of muscles(s) or muscle groups of variable topography (axial, proximal limb, distal). Myoclonus is less regularly repetitive and less sustained than is clonus.
A increased anteroposterior thickness of the cornea.
A reduced concentration of free thyroxine (fT4) in the blood circulation.
Underdevelopment of the bony pelvis.
Abnormal tortuous (i.e., twisted) form of the carotid arteries.
An abnormality of a homocysteine metabolic process.
Saccadic undershoot of horizontal saccadic eye movements, i.e., a horizontal saccadic eye movement that has less than the magnitude that would be required to gain fixation of the object.
Any deviation from the normal circulating concentration of chylomicrons.
A neurenteric cyst located in the spine.
A type of cataract that is not apparent at birth but that arises in childhood or adolescence.
A markedly blue coloration of the iris.
Immunohistochemistry reveals reduced emerin protein in the muscle biopsy.
A type of epileptic spasm of generalized onset.
A patchwork of intermingled areas of increased and decreased attenuation visualized on pulmonary high-resolution computed tomography.

A focal motor seizure in which the initial semiological manifestation is the sustained contraction of both agonist and antagonist muscles producing athetoid or twisting movements, which produces abnormal postures.
Absence or underdevelopment of the cochlea, a spiral shaped cavity in the inner ear, owing to a developmental defect.
Antihelical ridge that forms an acute angle between the antitragus and its bifurcation (stem) instead of a gently curving arc.
A malformation of the neural tube with a large amount of protruding brain tissue and absence of calvarium.
A congenital inclusion cysts that arises from ectodermal cells that normally form skin cells being left behind in the nervous system during development.
Periodic spells of incoordination and imbalance, that is, episodes of ataxia typically lasting from 10 minutes to several hours or days.
Abnormally increased caliber of the left subclavian artery.

Upturning of the big toe (and sometimes fanning of the other toes) in response to stimulation of the sole of the foot. If the Babinski sign is present it can indicate damage to the corticospinal tract.

A form of watery eye associated with overproduction of tears due to an increased parasympathetic drive to the secretory component of the lacrimal system (lacrimal gland); this could be due to pro-secretory drug use (e.g. pilocarpine) or autonomic disturbance.
Abnormal response to collagen or collagen-mimetics as manifested by reduced or lacking aggregation of platelets upon addition collagen or collagen-mimetics.
A decrease in the level of creatine in the brain identified by magnetic resonance spectroscopy (MRS).
Any structural abnormality of the telencephalon, which is also known as the cerebrum.
An anatomical anomaly that results from an abnormal rotation of the gut as it returns to the abdominal cavity during embryogenesis.
An abnormal reduction in the ability to masticate (chew), i.e., in the ability to crush and ground food in preparation for swallowing.

An ocular motility abnormality characterized by an overacting superior oblique muscle resulting to vertical incomitance of the eyes in lateral gaze. On examination, this is commonly seen as a downshoot of the adducting eye occuring when gaze is directed into the field of action of the inferior oblique muscle, producing a greater downward excursion of the adducted eye than of the abducted eye.
Abnormal outpouching or sac-like dilatation in the wall of the inferior mesenteric artery or superior mesenteric artery .
Heart rate of greater than 100 beats per minute.
Underdevelopment of part or all of the male external reproductive organs (which include the penis, the scrotum and the urethra).

An abnormal echotexture visible in liver ultrasound manifesting as a diffuse hyperechoic liver echotexture with multiple, small hypoechoic lesions. The appearance is said to resemble a starry sky (multiple white spots on a dark background).
An increased proportion of terminal hairs compared to vellus hairs.
The condition of having both rods and cones, but only a single kind of cone. Affected individuals have good pattern vision in daylight, but cannot distinguish between colors.
An extreme form of generalized edema with widespread and massive edema due to effusion of fluid into the extracellular space.
A vertical gaze palsy with inability to direct the gaze of the eyes downwards.
An anomalous location and arrangement of platelet alpha granules.

Persistence beyond the normal age (roughly the first half of the first year of life) of the asymmetric tonic neck reflex (ATNR), which is an easily elicited primitive reflex in the immediate newborn period. The ATNR refers to the phenomenon whereby when the face of an infant is turned to one side, the ipsilateral arm and leg extend and the contralateral arm and leg flex. This posture has been compared to a typical posture of fencers.

Abnormal small intestinal contractions, such as spasms and intestinal paralysis related to the loss of the ability of the gut to coordinate muscular activity because of endogenous or exogenous causes.
Abnormal amplitude of the QRS complex of the electrocardiogram (EKG).
A kinked appearance of the brainstem, i.e., an exaggerated flexure.
A defect of the chest wall characterized by a depression of the sternum, giving the chest ("pectus") a caved-in ("excavatum") appearance.
Hypersensitivity in form of an adverse immune reaction against gluten.
Truncal ataxia is a sign of ataxia characterized by instability of the trunk. It usually occurs during sitting.
Absence or abnormal closure of the choana (the posterior nasal aperture).
Neonatal electro-clinical seizure is an electrographic event occurring in neonatal period and coupled with a clinical manifestation.
Generalized excessive, abnormal hairiness.
An abnormality of the columella.
Increased anterosuperior prominence of the area between the bottom of the incisura and the inner margin of the antihelix.
An chronic form of hemolytic anemia.
Lack of dystrophin in muscle tissue. Immunohistochemistry reveals absent dystrophin protein in the muscle biopsy.
The presence of a dilated urinary bladder.
An abnormality of the malleus, an ossicle in the middle ear.
Accumulation of serous fluid (pale yellow and transparent fluid) in the pericardial sac.
Absence of axillary hair.

A Number 0 Tessier cleft is a true median cleft lip with a broad columella and bifid nasal tip. The alveolar cleft is between the central incisors. The nasal septum may be thickened, duplicated, or absent. The nasal bridge is usually broad with associated orbital hypertelorism. The midline soft tissue anomaly may range from a mild broadening of the philtrum or there may be a true median cleft lip. The columella and nasal tip are typically bifid and broadened with a midline depression. The alae nasi are intact but laterally displaced. The nose appears shortened in the vertical dimension.
An encapsulated collection of pus and necrotic material within the renal parenchyma. The destruction of renal parenchyma is associated with suppurative/neutrophil-rich inflammation and necrosis.
Immunohistochemistry reveals reduced dysferlin protein in the muscle biopsy.
A reduction in the length of time required for food to pass through the intestines.
A type of cataract that shows a spectacular display of multiple colours that glitters with the change of incident light like an illuminated Christmas tree.
Separation of the odontoid process from the body of the axis.
Abnormally increased levels of ethanolamine in circulation.
The presence of a moderate form of sensorineural hearing impairment.
An increase in the level of glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase in red blood cells.
Individuals affected by dichromacy possess only two types of cones, instead of three.

Ocular flutter is an abnormal eye movement consisting of repetitive, irregular, involuntary bursts of horizontal saccades without an intersaccadic interval. It is generally superimposed on normal oculomotor behaviour and its occurrence may be favoured by various events, such as blinks, the triggering of normal saccades or optokinetic stimulation.

A type of strabismus in which the fixating eye is always the same one, while the other eye is constantly deviated. Monocular strabismus is to be distinguished from alternating strabismus, in which either of the eyes 'squints' at different times.

Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy (HCM) is defined by the presence of increased ventricular wall thickness or mass in the absence of loading conditions (hypertension, valve disease) sufficient to cause the observed abnormality.
Episodic fever that recurs at regular intervals.
A confluent, generalized overgrowth of silvery blonde to gray lanugo hair at birth.
An abnormal increase in the level of lipoprotein cholesterol in the blood.

Stenosis of the cerebral aqueduct (also known as the mesencephalic duct, aqueductus mesencephali, or aqueduct of Sylvius), which connects the third cerebral ventricle in the diencephalon to the fourth ventricle, which is between the pons and cerebellum.
A type of cirrhosis characterized by the presence of small regenerative nodules.
A type of epileptic spasm of focal onset.
Reduction in diameter of the internal auditory canal.
Exaggerated anterior convexity of the thoracic vertebral column.

Medial degeneration of the aorta is to be used as an overarching term for any aortic surgical specimens that demonstrate one or more of the specific histopathologies mucoid extracellular matrix accumulation, elastic fiber fragmentation and/or loss, elastic fiber thinning, elastic fiber disorganization, smooth muscle cell nuclei loss, laminar medial collapse, smooth muscle cell disorganization, medial fibrosis. Grading of medial degeneration is based on the average overall severity of specific histopathologies as described, considering the worst area(s) sampled from multiple slides and aorta sections.
An unusually severe infection by a parainfluenza virus.
Decreased height of the intervertebral disk.
Any structural anomaly of the aortic valve leaflets.
Renal hypophosphatemia is defined as reduced serum phosphate (e.g., below 0.70 mmol/l) and an inappropriately high renal phosphate excretion.
A manifest or latent ocular deviation in which one or both eyes tends to deviate nasally.
Bradycardia related to a mean resting sinus rate of less than 50 beats per minute.

Parkinsonism is a clinical syndrome that is a feature of a number of different diseases, including Parkinson disease itself, other neurodegenerative diseases such as progressive supranuclear palsy, and as a side-effect of some neuroleptic medications. Some but not all individuals with Parkinsonism show responsiveness to dopaminergic medication defined as a substantial reduction of amelioration of the component signs of Parkinsonism (including mainly tremor, bradykinesia, rigidity, and postural instability) upon administration of dopaminergic medication.
A decreased concentration of citrulline in the blood.
Abnormally increased levels of ornithine in cerebrospinal fluid.
An increase in the level of N-acetyl aspartate in the brain identified by magnetic resonance spectroscopy (MRS).
A subnormal concentration of 18-Hydroxycorticosterone level in the blood circulation.
The presence of two to five cafe-au-lait macules.
A reduced level of the complement component Factor I in circulation.
Reduced uptake of [18F]-fluorodeoxyglucose (FDG) in the parietal cortex as measured by positron emission tomography (PET) brain scan.
Absence or underdevelopment of the clavicles (collar bones).
Complete absence of all von Willebrand factor multimers.
A congenital malformation of the aortic valve characterized by leaflet deformation.
Behavior that is not in line with social norms.
An increase in the level of glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase in tissue.
A type of conductive deafness with congenital onset.
Co-occurrence of the cystic pattern and the ground-glass pattern on pulmonary high-resolution computed tomography,
An abnormal prolongation of the miniature endplate potentials, i.e. the postsynaptic response to transmitter released from an individual vesicle at the neuromuscular junction.
The presence of extremely large cells with multiple nuclei. The so-called giant cells are thought to be of macrophage origin.
Enlargement of the thyroid gland related to a singular nodule in the thyroid gland.
An abnormality of an artery of lower lip.

Cornea plana is an abnormally flat shape of the cornea such that the normal protrusion of the cornea from the sclera is missing. The reduced corneal curvature can lead to hyperopia, and a hazy corneal limbus and arcus lipoides may develop at an early age.
A decreased amount of dystrophin in muscle fiber tissue.
Intense anterior chamber flare (fibrin/plastic aqueous).
An abnormality of the choroid and retina.
A term to describe when farsightedness is masked when the accommodative muscles are used to increase the focusing power of the eye.

Irregular lines in the deep retina that are typically configured in a radiating fashion and emanate from the optic disc. Angioid streaks are crack-like dehiscences in abnormally thickened and calcified Bruch's membrane, resulting in atrophy of the overlying retinal pigment epithelium. They may be associated with a number of endocrine, metabolic, and connective tissue abnormalities but are frequently idiopathic.
Fixation of an object in the area adjacent to the fovea.
A decreased amount of alpha sarcoglycan in muscle. Immunohistochemistry reveals reduced alpha sarcoglycan protein in the muscle biopsy.
Reduced width of the chest from side to side, associated with a reduced distance from the sternal notch to the tip of the shoulder.
A deformity of the chest caused by overgrowth of the ribs and characterized by protrusion of the sternum.
The presence of one or more herniated nucleus pulposus of intervertebral disk.
A wartlike (with multiple small elevated projections) papule.
A decreased anteroposterior thickness of the cornea.
A form of hemolytic anemia with congenital onset.
Loss of all hair on the entire body.
Accumulation of blood within the pericardial sac.
A structural anomaly of the mucous lining of the small intestine.
Edema/fluid accumulating within the retinal layers.
The presence of multiple xanthomas (xanthomata) in the skin distributed in the creases of the palm of the hand. Xanthomas are yellowish, firm, lipid-laden nodules in the skin.
Double rather than single peak of the antitragus.

A decrease in the ability to perceive vibration. Clinically, this is usually tested with a tuning fork which vibrates at 128 Hz and is applied to bony prominences such as the malleoli at the ankles or the metacarpal-phalangeal joints. There is a slow decay of vibration from the tuning fork. The degree of vibratory sense loss can be crudely estimated by counting the number of seconds that the examiner can perceive the vibration longer than the patient.
Abnormal narrowing of the choana (the posterior nasal aperture).
Increased size of epiphyses.
Abnormally increased width of the Z-disk of the sarcomere, resulting from splitting or opening of the Z-disc (c.f., Figure 2 of PMID:28732005).

Dilated cardiomyopathy (DCM) is defined by the presence of left ventricular dilatation and left ventricular systolic dysfunction in the absence of abnormal loading conditions (hypertension, valve disease) or coronary artery disease sufficient to cause global systolic impairment. Right ventricular dilation and dysfunction may be present but are not necessary for the diagnosis.
A solid, raised, plateau-like (flat-topped) lesion greater than 1 cm in diameter and that has a yellow color.
Any morphological abnormality of the cervical vertebral column.
Reduced uptake of [18F]-fluorodeoxyglucose (FDG) in the hypothalamus as measured by positron emission tomography (PET) brain scan.
Deposits accumulating between the retinal pigment epithelium and Bruch's membrane.
An increase in size of the anatomic space between the arachnoid membrane and pia mater in the region surrounding the cerebellum.
Posterior positioning of the nasal root in relation to the overall facial profile for age.
Lack of alpha sarcoglycan in muscle. Immunohistochemistry reveals absent alpha sarcoglycan protein in the muscle biopsy.
Dilation of central canal from incomplete fusion of the posterior columns or persistence of the primitive large canal of the embryo.
Abnormally increased hair growth with a localized distribution.
